      It=E2=80=99s SEC silly season
   =20
 =20

Many companies=C2=A0do at least a=C2=A0little=C2=A0bit of earnings manageme=
nt and =E2=80=9Cwindow dressing.=E2=80=9D If it is getting to be mid-to-lat=
e December and there is a sale that you have almost=C2=A0closed, or an expe=
nse that you=E2=80=99ll probably have to pay pretty soon, you will sit down=
 and say =E2=80=9Cwell, our year is almost over, do we want this sale (or e=
xpense) to count for this year, or next year?=E2=80=9D The answer will depe=
nd on your particular situation, but often you will=C2=A0want to book reven=
ue early and expenses late: You=E2=80=99ll rush to close the sale in Decemb=
er, and foot-drag on paying the expense until January, so that you can repo=
rt higher income for this fiscal year. You want this year to look as good a=
s possible; you=E2=80=99ll worry about next year later.
As an official matter, the US Securities and Exchange Commission frowns upo=
n this sort of thing; there are  rules and  enforcement actions. But the SE=
C=E2=80=99s fiscal year ends on Sept. 30 and, let me tell you, there sure w=
ere a lot of high-dollar enforcement actions last week. =E2=80=9CWall Stree=
t=E2=80=99s top regulator on Friday brought in $218 million in fines, rough=
ly equal to 10% of its latest annual budget,=E2=80=9D  counts the Wall Stre=
et Journal. I count  seven enforcement actions, against 16 firms, just on F=
riday, plus five more on Thursday.
  [1]
=C2=A0Could any of those cases have waited until Monday? Well. Now is a dif=
ferent fiscal year!=C2=A0You want to meet your earnings expectations.
I am kidding, I think? I am not really sure.=C2=A0Anyway lots of cases; let=
=E2=80=99s go through some of them quickly.

