 =20
   =20
      SEC: Whistleblowers
   =20
 =20

Here is  one against D.E. Shaw & Co., the big hedge fund, for violating whi=
stleblower laws. For a long time, hedge funds (and many other employers) ha=
ve asked employees to sign nondisclosure=C2=A0agreements that traditionally=
 say=C2=A0something like=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou agree not to disclose any confid=
ential information unless you are required to by law or a court order.=E2=
=80=9D Sometimes they also add =E2=80=9Cand, if you are required to disclos=
e it by law, you=E2=80=99ll tell us first.=E2=80=9D
The SEC takes the position that this is illegal. If your hedge fund is doin=
g fraud, and you learn about that in the course of your employment, then (1=
) the SEC would like you to come in and blow the whistle on your employer b=
ut (2) your nondisclosure agreement says that you can=E2=80=99t: The fraud =
is confidential information of the fund, and you=E2=80=99re not allowed to =
disclose it unless=C2=A0required to by=C2=A0law. In theory, if you went in =
to the SEC as a voluntary whistleblower and said =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s so=
me bad stuff,=E2=80=9D the SEC might investigate and fine your firm, and th=
en they might turn around and sue you saying =E2=80=9Csure we were doing fr=
aud but you weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0legally required=C2=A0to disclose it, that=
 was just a choice you made, and it violated your NDA.=E2=80=9D Obviously t=
hey would not do that,=C2=A0because it would be a bad look but also because=
 it is prohibited by whistleblower protection laws. But the language of the=
 NDA makes it possible, so arguably the NDA is itself illegal, a violation =
of whistleblower laws: The abstract theoretical threat of being sued for go=
ing to the SEC is enough to deter whistleblowers.
The SEC has sued firms over this before, and in 2017, after some of those c=
ases,=C2=A0D.E. Shaw sent an email to its employees being like =E2=80=9Cobv=
iously we don=E2=80=99t mean that.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CThe firm wishes to em=
phasize that you also have the ability to communicate directly with regulat=
ors and other governmental agencies regarding possible violations of law or=
 regulation without notice to the firm.=E2=80=9D) Still the employment agre=
ements kept using the old language until 2019. Also, for a while, when peop=
le left D.E. Shaw, to get severance, they had to sign a form saying that th=
ey had not filed any complaints about the firm with =E2=80=9Cany regulatory=
 authority,=E2=80=9D which also seems a little anti-whistleblower-y.
D.E. Shaw paid $10 million. I hope somebody is getting a whistleblower paym=
ent for this? Maybe the easiest lucrative job in finance is:
=09Take a job at a hedge fund.=09Get handed an employment agreement on the =
first day that says =E2=80=9Cyou agree not to disclose any of our secrets u=
nless required by law.=E2=80=9D=09Sign.=09Take the agreement home with you.=
=09Circle that sentence in red marker, write =E2=80=9C$$$$$!!!!!=E2=80=9D n=
ext to it and send it to the SEC.=09The SEC extracts a $10 million fine.=C2=
=A0=09They  give you $3 million.=09You can keep your job! Why not; it=E2=80=
=99s illegal to retaliate against whistleblowers.=09Or, you know, get a new=
 one and do it again.

Anyway there is no indication that D.E. Shaw did anything else wrong, or th=
at anyone was deterred from whistleblowing or whatever; this is just the pr=
ice of writing the wrong sentence in the NDA.

 =20
   =20
      SEC: Cell phones
   =20
 =20

Here are  two more=C2=A0enforcement actions=C2=A0from Friday about =E2=80=
=9Coff-channel communications.=E2=80=9D We have  talked a  lot about the SE=
C's theory that (1) it is illegal for employees of a financial firm to talk=
 about work on WhatsApp, personal text messaging, or other nonofficial chan=
nels and (2) since employees at literally every financial firm have done th=
is, there=E2=80=99s a lot of money to be extracted. The rate for big banks =
was about $125 million per bank paid to the SEC (the Commodity Futures Trad=
