The situation at Sculptor is:
=09Sculptor Capital Management Inc., a publicly traded asset management fir=
m, put itself up for auction last year, and this July it  signed an agreeme=
nt to sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp. for $11.15 per share. Rithm would =
keep Sculptor=E2=80=99s chief executive officer and chief investment office=
r, Jimmy Levin, around to run the Sculptor hedge funds. (Sculptor also has =
a real estate fund and a collateralized loan obligation business.)=09After =
the Rithm deal was announced, a group of hedge fund managers led by Boaz We=
instein   offered to buy Sculptor for $12.25 per share.=09Sculptor=E2=80=99=
s board said no, objecting that the Weinstein group=E2=80=99s financing was=
 too uncertain.=09So they went back and got committed financing for the who=
le thing, and     raised their bid to $12.76 per share.=09Sculptor=E2=80=99=
s board   said no again, complaining that the Weinstein group=E2=80=99s dea=
l is contingent on most of Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients (50.1% of the hedge-f=
und clients and 80% of the real estate and CLO clients) consenting to the d=
eal. Rithm=E2=80=99s is too =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s contingent on 85% o=
f clients consenting =E2=80=94=C2=A0but Rithm will leave Levin in charge, w=
hile Weinstein will presumably put himself in charge, and the board worries=
 that clients won=E2=80=99t consent to that.=C2=A0=09Sculptor=E2=80=99s boa=
rd told Weinstein how to fix the problem, though: Drop the client consent c=
ondition. This was a=C2=A0weird=C2=A0ask, in that most asset-management dea=
ls do have a client consent condition. In fact when Sculptor auctioned itse=
lf,=C2=A0it proposed=C2=A0an 80% client consent condition to all bidders. I=
t is strange for Sculptor to now say that the condition it proposed is unac=
ceptable. But, sure. =E2=80=9CIf [the Consortium] believe[s] that [its] mem=
bers=E2=80=99 reputation and experience are such that clients would in fact=
 grant their consent, then [the Consortium], and not the Company=E2=80=99s =
stockholders, should bear the risk of obtaining the client [run-rate] conse=
nts,=E2=80=9D said Sculptor.
  [3]



One possible analysis of this situation is that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is=
 trying to get the best possible deal for its shareholders. Yes, $12.76 is =
more than $11.15, but the board is probably right that there=E2=80=99s more=
 risk of clients saying no to Weinstein than to Rithm, because Weinstein re=
ally would change the management and strategy of the firm. If Weinstein rea=
lly wants Sculptor, and really thinks that he can keep the clients, then he=
 should drop the condition and just agree to buy Sculptor no matter how man=
y clients do or don=E2=80=99t come along. Perhaps he=E2=80=99s right that t=
hey=E2=80=99d all come along, but if they don=E2=80=99t that should be his =
problem.
But another possible analysis of the situation is that Sculptor=E2=80=99s b=
oard is friendly with Jimmy Levin, they like him, they want him to keep his=
 job and his nice paycheck, they suspect that the Weinstein bid is part of =
a vendetta by   Dan Och (Sculptor=E2=80=99s founder and Levin=E2=80=99s est=
ranged former mentor) to get back at Levin, and they prefer the lower Rithm=
 bid to the higher Weinstein bid because it lets Levin keep his job. The cl=
ient consent stuff is just an excuse, a way to say =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s=
 no deal unless Jimmy Levin stays in charge=E2=80=9D without actually sayin=
g it. This would be=C2=A0bad, a violation of the board=E2=80=99s fiduciary =
duties to its shareholders.=C2=A0
So far the board=E2=80=99s approach is=C2=A0working, for shareholders, in t=
hat Weinstein keeps raising his number and has now  dropped the consent con=
dition. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Hema Parmar, Katherine Burton=C2=A0and Sonali=
 Basak report:

Boaz Weinstein sweetened his bid for Sculptor Capital Management Inc., boos=
ting his price and conceding to so-called client-consent terms that had bec=
ome a sticking point with the hedge fund firm. The shares jumped more than =
6%.
The moves put pressure on Sculptor to consider his deal =E2=80=94 the lates=
t development in a saga that has captivated Wall Street as the two groups f=
ight for the struggling company.
It also prompted Rithm Capital Corp. to weigh a sweetened offer of its own,=
 according to people familiar with the matter.
A consortium of deep-pocketed investors led by Weinstein approached Sculpto=
r more than a week ago with an offer of at least $13 a share, up from an ea=
rlier bid of $12.76, said the people, who asked not to be identified discus=
sing confidential information.
The coalition also loosened its client-consent terms =E2=80=94 essentially =
agreeing to go through with the transaction even if all investors in its tw=
o hedge fund strategies reject it, the people said. The clauses were a key =
concern Sculptor had with Weinstein=E2=80=99s previous bid. For Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s other two strategies, the clauses remain as=C2=A0agreed=C2=A0upon i=
n July. Rithm=E2=80=99s offer, meanwhile, allows it to back out if more tha=
n 15% of Sculptor clients, as measured by fees paid, oppose the deal.

(Weinstein still wants 80% consents from clients of the real estate and CLO=
 businesses, where the strategy and management would not change much; this =
is, again, what Sculptor originally proposed.)
There are roughly three ways for this to go now:
=09The board says yes and takes the Weinstein deal with the higher price.=
=09The board finds another excuse to stick with the Rithm deal that keeps L=
evin.=09Rithm raises its bid and the highest price wins.

The problem is that it is hard, from the outside, to evaluate the board=E2=
=80=99s performance, because saying no to Weinstein could be=C2=A0either=C2=
=A0a way to protect Levin=E2=80=99s job at the expense of shareholders,=C2=
=A0or a clever tactic to get Weinstein to raise his bid and drop his condit=
ions. Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders are way better off now than they woul=
d have been if Sculptor had accepted Weinstein=E2=80=99s original $12.25 of=
fer. As long as Sculptor actually ends up accepting a higher offer.

