      AI hedge funds
   =20
 =20

Will a robot ultimately be better than humans at picking stocks that will g=
o up? I feel like the basic answer is =E2=80=9Csure, obviously,=E2=80=9D th=
ough there are weird nuances to that. (If it=E2=80=99s true, then eventuall=
y=C2=A0the market will be=C2=A0all=C2=A0robots, and then to outperform the =
market you will need to be a better robot than all the other robots. Invest=
ing performance is not absolute but relative.) But, I mean, sure, obviously=
. There is a bunch of data, some bits of the past data are correlated with =
particular bits of future data, and surely a computer has more stamina and =
memory to search for complex predictive patterns in the data. It just feels=
 like one of those long-run leave-it-to-the-robots businesses.
On the other hand it is a slow and iterative process to get those robots to=
 where they need to be, just like it is for, say, self-driving cars. The pr=
oblem with building self-driving cars before the technology is perfected is=
 that sometimes they crash. The problem with building investing robots befo=
re the technology is perfected is that sometimes they lose money. Bloomberg=
=E2=80=99s   Justina Lee reports:

The irony of investors=E2=80=99 piling into AI is that the technology has f=
or years struggled to crack the actual business of investing. Machines get =
bamboozled by noisy markets and can be caught off guard by fickle trends, a=
nd finance=E2=80=94surprisingly=E2=80=94sometimes lacks the oceans of data =
that underpin the technology in other domains.
A Eurekahedge index of 12 funds using AI has trailed its broader hedge fund=
 index by about 14 percentage points over the past five years. According to=
 Plexus Investments, an asset manager that tracks the returns of boutique A=
I funds, only 45% outperform the benchmarks they measure themselves against=
.
While that may seem disappointing to anyone watching AI upend other fields,=
 it=E2=80=99s comparable to the average performance of human stock pickers.=
 =E2=80=9CToday, AI and machine learning can already compete with tradition=
al fund managers,=E2=80=9D says Andreas Vogel, a senior analyst at Plexus. =
In other words, you don=E2=80=99t need to hire expensive portfolio managers=
 when a computer can give you similar results.

The other puzzle is what counts as =E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D. There is sort of a=
 fuzzy line between =E2=80=9Cartificial intelligence develops our investing=
 strategy=E2=80=9D and, like, =E2=80=9Cwe run a bunch of regressions on his=
torical data to identify signals, and then we program those signals into a =
trading system=E2=80=9D:

The promise has made Jason Hsu a convert. Hsu was an old-school quant, shor=
thand for =E2=80=9Cquantitative investor,=E2=80=9D money managers who use c=
omputers to crunch piles of numbers and then pick securities. Like most qua=
nts, he believed in a handful of simple investing rules developed over deca=
des by academics studying the behavior of markets and picking stocks based =
on characteristics such as their valuation or size. In 2002, Hsu co-founded=
 Research Affiliates, which now manages some $130 billion in assets.
With the backing of the firm, Hsu founded a company in 2016 called Rayliant=
 Global Advisors, and soon he underwent an AI epiphany. His team showed him=
 the hypothetical results of an investing strategy designed by machines, an=
d now most of the firm=E2=80=99s funds are run by an algorithm called eXtre=
me Gradient Boosting. The manager of about $17 billion parses some 200 sign=
als, using a form of decision tree to identify often complex relationships =
and make buy or sell decisions. =E2=80=9CIt took us a while to convince our=
selves,=E2=80=9D Hsu says. =E2=80=9CThen we finally got to a place where we=
 said, =E2=80=98We see the value. We get the benefits.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D
By Silicon Valley standards, Rayliant=E2=80=99s methods are almost old-fash=
ioned. Yet they=E2=80=99re a big leap for a money manager who started out p=
icking stocks based on just six criteria, and a good illustration of the wa=
y AI promises to revolutionize investing: not loud or dramatic, just a seri=
es of tweaks, techniques and enhancements bearing impenetrable names like =
=E2=80=9Csupport vector machines=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Clong short-term memor=
y.=E2=80=9D

Basically all professional investing is =E2=80=9Cusing computers to crunch =
piles of numbers and then pick securities,=E2=80=9D with a gradation betwee=
n using Excel and using support vector machines.

