ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  said no again</a>, complaining that the Weinstein group=E2=80=99s deal is=
 contingent on most of Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients (50.1% of the hedge-fund =
clients and 80% of the real estate and CLO clients) consenting to the deal.=
 Rithm=E2=80=99s is too =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s contingent on 85% of cl=
ients consenting =E2=80=94=C2=A0but Rithm will leave Levin in charge, while=
 Weinstein will presumably put himself in charge, and the board worries tha=
t clients won=E2=80=99t consent to that.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s board told Weinstein how to fix the problem=
, though: Drop the client consent condition. This was a=C2=A0<em>weird=C2=
=A0</em>ask, in that most asset-management deals do have a client consent c=
ondition. In fact when Sculptor auctioned itself,=C2=A0<em>it proposed=C2=
=A0</em>an 80% client consent condition to all bidders. It is strange for S=
culptor to now say that the condition it proposed is unacceptable. But, sur=
e. =E2=80=9CIf [the Consortium] believe[s] that [its] members=E2=80=99 repu=
tation and experience are such that clients would in fact grant their conse=
nt, then [the Consortium], and not the Company=E2=80=99s stockholders, shou=
ld bear the risk of obtaining the client [run-rate] consents,=E2=80=9D said=
 Sculptor.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possible analysis of this situation is tha=
t Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is trying to get the best possible deal for its =
shareholders. Yes, $12.76 is more than $11.15, but the board is probably ri=
ght that there=E2=80=99s more risk of clients saying no to Weinstein than t=
o Rithm, because Weinstein really would change the management and strategy =
of the firm. If Weinstein really wants Sculptor, and really thinks that he =
can keep the clients, then he should drop the condition and just agree to b=
uy Sculptor no matter how many clients do or don=E2=80=99t come along. Perh=
aps he=E2=80=99s right that they=E2=80=99d all come along, but if they don=
=E2=80=99t that should be his problem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another possible analysis of the situation=
 is that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is friendly with Jimmy Levin, they like h=
im, they want him to keep his job and his nice paycheck, they suspect that =
the Weinstein bid is part of a vendetta by <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/32912729.260424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMzAvc2N1bHB0b3ItaXMtZnVsbC1vZi1jb25mbGljd=
HM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAwMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNl=
PW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB2df9f3d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Dan Och</a> (Sculptor=E2=80=99s foun=
der and Levin=E2=80=99s estranged former mentor) to get back at Levin, and =
they prefer the lower Rithm bid to the higher Weinstein bid because it lets=
 Levin keep his job. The client consent stuff is just an excuse, a way to s=
ay =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s no deal unless Jimmy Levin stays in charge=E2=
=80=9D without actually saying it. This would be=C2=A0<em>bad</em>, a viola=
tion of the board=E2=80=99s fiduciary duties to its shareholders.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So far the board=E2=80=99s approach is=C2=A0<e=
m>working</em>, for shareholders, in that Weinstein keeps raising his numbe=
r and has now  dropped the consent condition. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32912729.260424/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDIvd2VpbnN0ZWluLXJh=
aXNlcy1zY3VscHRvci1iaWQtYWdhaW4tYXMtcml0aG0td2VpZ2hzLWhpZ2hlci1vZmZlcj9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQxMDAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB8d6e6cd1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Hema Parmar, Katherine Burton=C2=A0and Sona=
li Basak report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Boaz Weinstein sweetened his bid for Sculptor =
Capital Management Inc., boosting his price and conceding to so-called clie=
nt-consent terms that had become a sticking point with the hedge fund firm.=
 The shares jumped more than 6%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The moves put pressure on Sculptor to consider=
 his deal =E2=80=94 the latest development in a saga that has captivated Wa=
ll Street as the two groups fight for the struggling company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also prompted Rithm Capital Corp. to weigh =
a sweetened offer of its own, according to people familiar with the matter.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A consortium of deep-pocketed investors led by=
 Weinstein approached Sculptor more than a week ago with an offer of at lea=
st $13 a share, up from an earlier bid of $12.76, said the people, who aske=
d not to be identified discussing confidential information.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The coalition also loosened its client-consent=
 terms =E2=80=94 essentially agreeing to go through with the transaction ev=
en if all investors in its two hedge fund strategies reject it, the people =
said. The clauses were a key concern Sculptor had with Weinstein=E2=80=99s =
previous bid. For Sculptor=E2=80=99s other two strategies, the clauses rema=
in as=C2=A0agreed=C2=A0upon in July. Rithm=E2=80=99s offer, meanwhile, allo=
ws it to back out if more than 15% of Sculptor clients, as measured by fees=
 paid, oppose the deal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(Weinstein still wants 80% consents from clien=
ts of the real estate and CLO businesses, where the strategy and management=
 would not change much; this is, again, what Sculptor originally proposed.)=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are roughly three ways for this to go no=
w:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The board says yes and takes the Wein=
stein deal with the higher price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
The board finds another excuse to stick with the Rithm deal that keeps Levi=
n.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Rithm raises its bid and the hi=
ghest price wins.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that it is hard, from the outsi=
de, to evaluate the board=E2=80=99s performance, because saying no to Weins=
tein could be=C2=A0<em>either=C2=A0</em>a way to protect Levin=E2=80=99s jo=
b at the expense of shareholders,=C2=A0<em>or </em>a clever tactic to get W=
einstein to raise his bid and drop his conditions. Sculptor=E2=80=99s share=
holders are way better off now than they would have been if Sculptor had ac=
cepted Weinstein=E2=80=99s original $12.25 offer. As long as Sculptor actua=
lly ends up accepting a higher offer.</p>
