<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Will a robot ultimately be better than humans =
at picking stocks that will go up? I feel like the basic answer is =E2=80=
=9Csure, obviously,=E2=80=9D though there are weird nuances to that. (If it=
=E2=80=99s true, then eventually=C2=A0the market will be=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0=
</em>robots, and then to outperform the market you will need to be a better=
 robot than all the other robots. Investing performance is not absolute but=
 relative.) But, I mean, sure, obviously. There is a bunch of data, some bi=
ts of the past data are correlated with particular bits of future data, and=
 surely a computer has more stamina and memory to search for complex predic=
tive patterns in the data. It just feels like one of those long-run leave-i=
t-to-the-robots businesses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand it is a slow and iterative p=
rocess to get those robots to where they need to be, just like it is for, s=
ay, self-driving cars. The problem with building self-driving cars before t=
he technology is perfected is that sometimes they crash. The problem with b=
uilding investing robots before the technology is perfected is that sometim=
es they lose money. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/32912729.260424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDMvY2FuLWFpLXBpY2stc3RvY2tzLWJldHRlci10aGFuLXdh=
bGwtc3RyZWV0LWZpcm1zLWFyZS10cnlpbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAwMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDAzJnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3b6c297f" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Jus=
tina Lee reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The irony of investors=E2=80=99 piling into AI=
 is that the technology has for years struggled to crack the actual busines=
s of investing. Machines get bamboozled by noisy markets and can be caught =
off guard by fickle trends, and finance=E2=80=94surprisingly=E2=80=94someti=
mes lacks the oceans of data that underpin the technology in other domains.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Eurekahedge index of 12 funds using AI has t=
railed its broader hedge fund index by about 14 percentage points over the =
past five years. According to Plexus Investments, an asset manager that tra=
cks the returns of boutique AI funds, only 45% outperform the benchmarks th=
ey measure themselves against.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While that may seem disappointing to anyone wa=
tching AI upend other fields, it=E2=80=99s comparable to the average perfor=
mance of human stock pickers. =E2=80=9CToday, AI and machine learning can a=
lready compete with traditional fund managers,=E2=80=9D says Andreas Vogel,=
 a senior analyst at Plexus. In other words, you don=E2=80=99t need to hire=
 expensive portfolio managers when a computer can give you similar results.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other puzzle is what counts as =E2=80=9CAI=
=E2=80=9D. There is sort of a fuzzy line between =E2=80=9Cartificial intell=
igence develops our investing strategy=E2=80=9D and, like, =E2=80=9Cwe run =
a bunch of regressions on historical data to identify signals, and then we =
program those signals into a trading system=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The promise has made Jason Hsu a convert. Hsu =
was an old-school quant, shorthand for =E2=80=9Cquantitative investor,=E2=
=80=9D money managers who use computers to crunch piles of numbers and then=
 pick securities. Like most quants, he believed in a handful of simple inve=
sting rules developed over decades by academics studying the behavior of ma=
rkets and picking stocks based on characteristics such as their valuation o=
r size. In 2002, Hsu co-founded Research Affiliates, which now manages some=
 $130 billion in assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the backing of the firm, Hsu founded a co=
mpany in 2016 called Rayliant Global Advisors, and soon he underwent an AI =
epiphany. His team showed him the hypothetical results of an investing stra=
tegy designed by machines, and now most of the firm=E2=80=99s funds are run=
 by an algorithm called eXtreme Gradient Boosting. The manager of about $17=
 billion parses some 200 signals, using a form of decision tree to identify=
 often complex relationships and make buy or sell decisions. =E2=80=9CIt to=
ok us a while to convince ourselves,=E2=80=9D Hsu says. =E2=80=9CThen we fi=
nally got to a place where we said, =E2=80=98We see the value. We get the b=
enefits.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By Silicon Valley standards, Rayliant=E2=80=99=
s methods are almost old-fashioned. Yet they=E2=80=99re a big leap for a mo=
ney manager who started out picking stocks based on just six criteria, and =
a good illustration of the way AI promises to revolutionize investing: not =
loud or dramatic, just a series of tweaks, techniques and enhancements bear=
ing impenetrable names like =E2=80=9Csupport vector machines=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9Clong short-term memory.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically all professional investing is =E2=80=
=9Cusing computers to crunch piles of numbers and then pick securities,=E2=
=80=9D with a gradation between using Excel and using support vector machin=
es.</p>
